<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ910402-0015</DOCNO><DOCID>910402-0015.</DOCID><HL>   First City Bancorp. of Texas   Says It Will Post Loss for '91</HL><DATE>04/02/91</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A22</SO><CO>   FBT</CO><MS>FINANCIAL (FIN)</MS><IN>SOUTHERN U.S. BANKS (BAS)ALL REGIONAL BANKS (BAR)ALL BANKS, BANKING NEWS AND ISSUES (BNK)</IN><LP>   HOUSTON -- First City Bancorp. of Texas Inc., plagued bysouring loans and management turmoil, said it expects toreport a loss for 1991.   The disclosure, in a filing with the Securities andExchange Commission, didn't specify the magnitude of theanticipated loss, although the bank holding company hasalready said it expects to post a loss of between $50 millionand $75 million for the first quarter.</LP><TEXT>   A spokesman said the SEC filing also disclosed that FirstCity expects to negotiate agreements with federal regulatorsto address capital deficiencies and other problems at four ofits bank units.   Among other things, the company expects the agreement toinclude expanding the boards of the Houston, Dallas, SanAntonio and Austin banks to include outside directors, and to&quot;study management and the supervision of management&quot; by theindividual boards, the spokesman said.   Also, the filing indicated that A. Robert Abboud, who wasousted by the holding company board last week as chairman andchief executive officer, has served notice that he considersthe company has breached his management contract, thespokesman said. The spokesman added that the board isconsidering that matter.</TEXT></DOC>